            "answer_text": "This answer is off the subject, but involves French and Vietnam in 1966\u201367. I was a Marine in Vietnam 1966\u20131967 and stationed up north, just down from the DMZ. Dong Ha, Cam Lo, Con Thien, Rockpile, Camp JJ Carroll. Studied French in high school but wasn\u2019t worth a shit but the kind teacher passed me anyway. I knew that the French had occupied Vietnam for some time and would at times speak the language to some civilian Vietnamese, when we were around a ville. I could not speak Vietnamese and them no English, but we both could talk in French. Only dumb things, like \u201cwhat time is it\u201d or \u201cwhat color is that\u201d. And \u201chow are you\u201d. Nonetheless, it was really cool and it made the torturous French class much better. There were many bad things happening in Vietnam, but this was a nice thing . Now, spring ahead many years and my barber is a former Vietnamese Marine and very pro American and loves the USMC. No bullshit haircut. Sit down, shut up, and a Marine Corps haircut is on the way. He had a Vietnamese name, of course, but went by Long. I knew he was born in 1942 and asked him about speaking French and made the mistake to speak to him in French. He immediately reamed my ass, for my poor pronunciation, then told me he was required to speak French and spoke it to me and I swear he was a native, he was so good. Then he told me about the Japanese in WW2 and how he hated them, because they were in Vietnam. We both agreed that America was over there, to try and stop the commies. Everyone seems to forget that now. He was so kind, that if a serviceman came in and had no money, he would cut their hair for free. Unfortunately, I had to find a regular barber shop that had more than one barber. I would call before but with a one man shop, sometimes he was at lunch or the bank and it became a burden. He hung up his scissors when the coronavirus hit. I hope you enjoyed my ramblings! ",
