            },
            "answer_text": "I wasn\u2019t going to write an answer but accidentally read ridiculously hateful answers on this matter so I think I should provide my pov. Geez, people, chill! French is not largely spoken in Vietnam nowadays. It\u2019s a fact. I have my University major in French but rarely use the language for work, mostly it was English. But it\u2019s not necessary to say that French speaking people are rare in Vietnam. Not mention anymore of the \u2018old French speaking generation\u2019 which some people wrote about (my grandparents belong to this group, they were born in 20s-30s), there are many French speaking people from other generations actively use that language till this day. Just because of its own characteristics, French mostly learned today in Vietnam by people that work in History, Medicine, Architecture, Fine Arts, some in Engineering and Nature Sciences, or Social Sciences Studies\u2026ect Including alumni in other fields who studied in France or other French speaking countries. English, Japanese & Korean have more of their exposure in economic factors so it\u2019s easier to meet people know these languages in your working environment. Otherwise, I meet many French speaking people in cultural events, since the France institutes in Hanoi and Saigon are still two of the most active cultural spaces in Vietnam. Just my 50cent. I\u2019m from Hanoi by the way. ",
