            "author_info": {
                "name": "Imre Kovacs",
                "href": "/profile/Imre-Kovacs"
            },
            "answer_text": "French is a foreign language in contemporary Vietnam, it plays no special role, it is not spoken natively by Vietnamese in Vietnam, it is a school subject that is learned by some students as a foreign language, but probably far more learn English than French. Ethnologue does not even mention French among the languages spoken in Vietnam. The website you\u2019ve linked to is targeted at French speaking expats and French speakers around the world, I don\u2019t know if it is government backed or independent media, but it is definitely not the primary source of information for any Vietnamese (unless someone is a Frenchman of Vietnamese descent and does not speak Vietnamese at all). Many countries have such websites, magazines, so it\u2019s nothing special. I know that some people still entertain the idea that \u201cVietnam is some sort of ex-French country where you could get by if you speak French\u201d, but Vietnam is not like West Africa, where French is the language of administration and inter-ethnic communication, higher education, etc. Vietnam is a nation state with its own national language that is used as primary language in all areas of public life, including business. Of course you will find many educated Vietnamese who are fluent in foreign languages, mostly English, some other European languages including French, but also German, etc. and even speakers of Mandarin or Japanese. But those speakers owe their skills to foreign language education, studies abroad or family background (emigration to the West), not to the colonial period of Vietnam. ",
