            "author_info": {
                "name": "Philippe Fabre",
                "href": "/profile/Philippe-Fabre"
            },
            "answer_text": "No. The first time I visited HCMC in 1993, I had a 70 year-old partner who had been a former colonial government officer. He spoke some french that he learned in school. But his english was much better (he had also worked with the Americans) Even during the colonial time, not many Vietnamese were speaking french. The colonization ended in the 50\u2019s and there has been almost no french presence since that. However, during the war and for several years after, english was banned from schools (at least in the North) and french made a return in favor. I have indeed done business with several people born after the independence who had learned french. Especially in the North. Very difficult pronunciation because no use of the language. But nowadays, english has come back as the top foreign language and very few Vietnamese speak french. ",
